In the realm of modern artificial intelligence, the application of Classical Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) in image recognition has yielded remarkable results. Yet, the horizon of neural network innovation expands further with the introduction of Quantum Convolutional Neural Networks (QCNNs). QCNNs propose an intriguing new take on CNNs, incorporating quantum mechanisms that enhance their training process by reducing the input size from $n$ to $log\_2n$.

This research sets out to explore the capabilities of both CCNNs and QCNNs by meticulously comparing their performance on three popular image recognition datasets: the MNIST hand-written digits, Fashion MNIST, and Cat/Dog Face Images. Intriguingly, a technique widely adopted in CNNs to boost classification performance, namely Data Augmentation (DA), was also implemented within the quantum framework.

However, the findings were unexpected. While DA significantly improved the performance of CNNs on the given datasets, it failed to demonstrate any substantial enhancement in the QCNNs. This paper delves into the reasons behind this surprising outcome, shedding light on the intricacies of quantum machine learning theory and potentially expanding our collective understanding.

In the cutting-edge field of advanced artificial intelligence, the utilization of Classical Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) in image recognition has brought about impressive achievements. QCNNs offer a fresh twist on CNNs by integrating quantum principles, streamlining the training process by shrinking the input data from $n$ to $log\_2n$.

Our investigation aims to assess the strengths and limitations of both CCNNs and QCNNs by conducting a rigorous comparison of their efficacy on three renowned image recognition benchmarks: the MNIST handwritten digits, Fashion MNIST, and Cat/Dog Face Images. An intriguing development in this study involved the implementation of Data Augmentation (DA) – a widely used technique to bolster CNNs' classification capabilities – within the quantum framework.

Unexpectedly, the results did not align with our expectations. Although DA significantly amplified the performance of CNNs on the analyzed datasets, it showed minimal improvement for QCNNs. This paper aims to unravel the reasons behind this puzzling outcome, illuminating the complexities of quantum machine learning theory and paving the way for a more profound comprehension.
